-@title = "jQuery Mobile Docs - Methods"
= render :partial => "/mobile/index.js.haml", :format => :js

%div{"data-role" => "page"}
  %div{"data-role" => "header", "data-theme" => "b"}
    %h1 Methods
    %a.ui-btn-right.jqm-home{"data-direction" => "reverse", "data-icon" => "home", "data-iconpos" => "notext", :href => "/mobile"} Home
  / /header
  %div{"data-role" => "content"}
    %p jQuery Mobile exposes several methods and properties on the $.mobile object for use in your applications.
    %dl
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.changePage
        (
        %em> method
        )
      %dd Programmatically change from one page to another. This method is used internally for transitions that occur as a result of clicking a link or submitting a form, when those features are enabled.
      %dd
        %dl
          %dt Arguments
          %dd
            %code to
            %ul
              %li
                String, url to transition to (
                %code> "about/us.html"
                )
              %li
                jQuery object (
                %code> $("#about")
                )
              %li Array specifying two page references [from,to] for transitioning from a known page. From is otherwise assumed to be the current page in view (or $.mobile.activePage ).
              %li
                Object for sending form data. (
                %code {url: url, data: serialized form data, type: "get" or "post"}
          %dd
            %code transition
            (
            %em> string
            , examples: "pop", "slide"," "none")
          %dd
            %code back
            (
            %em> boolean
            , default: false). True will cause a reverse-direction transition.
          %dd
            %code changeHash
            (
            %em> boolean
            , default: true). Update the hash to the to page's URL when page change is complete.
      %dd
        Examples:
        %pre
          :preserve
            //transition to the "about us" page with a slideup transition
            $.mobile.changePage("about/us.html", "slideup");
            //transition to the "search results" page, using data from a form with an ID of "search""
            $.mobile.changePage({
              url: "searchresults.php",
              type: "get",
              data: $("form#search").serialize()
            });
            //transition to the "confirm" page with a "pop" transition without tracking it in history
            $.mobile.changePage("../alerts/confirm.html", "pop", false, false);
      %dt
        %code jqmData(), jqmRemoveData(), and jqmHasData()
        (
        %em> method
        )
      %dd
        When working with jQuery Mobile,
        %code jqmData
        and
        %code jqmRemoveData
        should be used in place of jQuery core's
        %code data
        and
        %code removeData
        methods (note that this includes $.fn.data, $.fn.removeData, and the $.data, $.removeData, and $.hasData utilities), as they automatically incorporate getting and setting of namespaced data attributes (even if no namespace is currently in use).
      %dd
        %dl
          %dt Arguments:
          %dd
            See jQuery's
            %a{:href => "http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.data/"} data
            and
            %a{:href => "http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.removeData/"} removeData
            methods
          %dt Also:
          %dd
            When finding elements by their jQuery Mobile data attribute, please use the custom selector
            = succeed "," do
              %code :jqmData()
            as it automatically incorporates namespaced data attributes into the lookup when they are in use. For example, instead of calling
            = succeed "," do
              %code $("div[data-role='page']")
            you should use
            = succeed "," do
              %code $("div:jqmData(role='page')")
            which internally maps to
            %code $("div[data-"+ $.mobile.ns +"role='page']")
            without forcing you to concatenate a namespace into your selectors manually.

      %dt
        %code $.mobile.pageLoading
        (
        %em> method
        )
      %dd Show or hide the page loading message, which is configurable via $.mobile.loadingMessage.
      %dd
        %dl
          %dt Arguments:
          %dd
            %code Done
            (
            %em> boolean
            , defaults to false, meaning loading has started). True will hide the loading message.
      %dd
        Examples:
        %pre
          :preserve
            //cue the page loader
            $.mobile.pageLoading();
            //hide the page loader
            $.mobile.pageLoading( true );
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.path
        (
        %em> methods, properties
        )
      %dd Utilities for getting, setting, and manipulating url paths. TODO: document as public API is finalized.
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.base
        (
        %em> methods, properties
        )
      %dd Utilities for working with generated base element. TODO: document as public API is finalized.
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.silentScroll
        (
        %em> method
        )
      %dd Scroll to a particular Y position without triggering scroll event listeners.
      %dd
        %dl
          %dt Arguments:
          %dd
            %code yPos
            (
            %em> number
            , defaults to 0). Pass any number to scroll to that Y location.
      %dd
        Examples:
        %pre
          :preserve
            //scroll to Y 100px
            $.mobile.silentScroll(100);
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.addResolutionBreakpoints
        (
        %em> method
        )
      %dd Add width breakpoints to the min/max width classes that are added to the HTML element.
      %dd
        %dl
          %dt Arguments:
          %dd
            %code values
            (
            %em> number or array
            ). Pass any number or array of numbers to add to the resolution classes. Read more about this feature here:
            = succeed "." do
              %a{:href => "/mobile/docs/api/mediahelpers"} Orientation &amp; resolution targeting
      %dd
        Examples:
        %pre
          :preserve
            //add a 400px breakpoint
            $.mobile.addResolutionBreakpoints(400);
            //add 2 more breakpoints
            $.mobile.addResolutionBreakpoints([600,800]);
      %dt
        %code $.mobile.activePage
        (
        %em> property
        )
      %dd Reference to the page currently in view.
  / /content
